In [29]:
# dealing with missing value in production_companies
# In this case , I suggested to fill this with mode
def missing_values(df, columns):
    for column in columns:
        df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].mode()[0])
    return df
df = missing_values(df,['production_companies'])

Research Question 8 ( Are there any relation between revenue and genres? )¶

In [38]:
# Find the top 10 most frequent genres
top_10_genres = df['genres'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index
df_top_10_genres = df[df['genres'].isin(top_10_genres)]
high_revenue_films = df_top_10_genres[df_top_10_genres['revenue_adj'] > df_top_10_genres['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.9)]
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=high_revenue_films, x='genres', y='revenue_adj')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.title('Revenue Distribution Across Genres for High-Revenue Films (Top 10 Genres)')
plt.xlabel('Genre')
plt.ylabel('Revenue (Adjusted)')
Out[38]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Revenue (Adjusted)')

Research Question 9 ( What is the popularity of genres over years with limit top 10 frequent genres ? )¶

In [39]:
top10genres = df["genres"].value_counts().nlargest(10).index
filtered_df = df[df["genres"].isin(top10genres)]
genre_year_count = filtered_df.groupby(["release_year", "genres"]).size().unstack()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
genre_year_count.plot(marker="o", linewidth=1)
plt.xlabel("Release Year")
plt.ylabel("Movie Count")
plt.title("Popularity of Top Genres Over Years")
plt.legend(title="Genres", loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))

Conclusions¶

From question 1:
The distribution of movie runtimes helps us understand the common lengths of movies in the dataset, identifying any outliers that may need further investigation.

From question 2:
Analyzing the popularity of movies over the years allows us to observe trends and fluctuations in audience interest in films across different time periods.

From question 3:
Identifying the top production companies with the highest average revenue provides insights into the key players in the industry that consistently produce financially successful movies.

From question 4:
Exploring the correlation between movie budget and revenue helps us understand the financial dynamics of filmmaking, including how investments in production budgets may impact revenue generation.

From question 5:
Examining the relationship between average vote rating and movie runtime allows us to assess how runtime duration may influence audience perception and rating of movies.

From question 6:
Investigating the relationship between movie runtime and popularity helps us understand whether longer movies tend to attract more attention and popularity among audiences.

From question 7:
Determining the top genres by average revenue sheds light on the most financially lucrative genres in the dataset, providing valuable insights for filmmakers and production companies.

From question 8:
Analyzing the revenue distribution across genres for high-revenue films allows us to explore potential associations between specific genres and revenue generation, aiding in genre-based decision-making in film production.

From question 9:
Exploring the popularity of genres over years with a focus on the top 10 frequent genres helps us track the evolving audience preferences and genre >rends over time, informing strategic decisions in film production and marketing.
